  "prompt": "Will Northern Ireland have an independence referendum after the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "The issue of an independence referendum for Northern Ireland following the Brexit vote is complex and politically sensitive. Northern Ireland remains part of the United Kingdom, but the Brexit vote has reignited discussions about its future. \n\nUnder the Good Friday Agreement (also known as the Belfast Agreement) of 1998, a referendum on Irish reunification can be called if it appears likely to the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland that a majority would favor a united Ireland. However, as of now, no definitive decision or date has been set for such a referendum.\n\nThe political landscape in Northern Ireland is divided, with some parties and communities supporting the idea of a referendum on Irish unity, while others wish to remain part of the UK. The Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) and other unionist groups oppose a referendum, whereas Sinn F\u00e9in and other nationalist parties advocate for it.\n\nPublic opinion polls have shown a slight shift in favor of Irish unity post-Brexit, but it remains a closely contested issue. The Northern Ireland Life and Times survey in 2020 indicated that a significant portion of the population still wishes to remain part of the UK, while support for a united Ireland has grown but not to a majority level.\n\nIn summary, while there is increased discussion and demand for an independence referendum in Northern Ireland following Brexit, no such referendum has been scheduled. The decision would ultimately hinge on the political climate, the Secretary of State's assessment, and broader public opinion.",
